c":0.82,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Symptom triage returns a clinician-reviewable natural-language explanation, not just a numeric score.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: explanation quality/completeness depends on real model generation; deterministic mocks would overstate reliability.","test_description":"Invoke real triage model with representative symptom inputs and assert response includes free-text rationale meeting schema and minimum-content checks (mentions key symptoms + urgency rationale), not only scalar urgency fields.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.74,"Workflow":0.08}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"Appointment is scheduled in first available slot matching urgency SLA (high: same-day, medium: within 48 hours).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: scheduling correctness depends on scheduler logic + shared calendar DB query/write behavior and time-window filtering; pure unit tests can miss ordering and persistence interactions.","test_description":"Seed local calendar DB with controlled availability. Run scheduling service with high and medium urgencies via real repository layer. Assert selected slot is earliest valid one and respects same-day/48-hour policy windows.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"Scheduling does not double-book a slot when two patients are processed concurrently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is concurrency + DB transaction/locking semantics across scheduler and calendar store. In-process mocks often hide race conditions.","test_description":"Using real calendar DB constraints/transactions, run two concurrent scheduling requests targeting same scarce slot. Assert exactly one booking succeeds for that slot and the other request gets next valid slot or conflict outcome per spec.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.22,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":9,"description":"Confirmation message includes patient name, appointment time, provider name, and visit-type-specific preparation instructions.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Cross-module data binding (scheduler output + template + visit-type rules) is the main risk; unit template tests alone can miss missing-field wiring regressions.","test_description":"Execute confirmation generation from a persisted appointment record for multiple visit types. Assert rendered message contains required fields and correct preparation instructions for each type.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.33,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":10,"description":"Full intake pipeline (validate, insurance, triage, schedule, confirm) completes for a real patient submission without manual intervention.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: this is an end-to-end pipeline with sequential dependencies including an agentic triage step; real failures emerge from cross-step handoffs and cumulative state transitions.","test_description":"Submit a realistic patient intake through production orchestration against test infra: real HTTP payer stub (with deterministic status), real triage model/API, real calendar DB, and confirmation channel sink. Assert successful terminal state plus artifacts from every stage with no human fallback path triggered.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.28,"Workflow":0.58}}]}
